               <msContents>
                  <summary>The Báb's Commentary on the <title key="work_23757">Súratu'l-Kawthar (Qur'án 108)</title>.
                     Browne cites internal and external evidence (the Tárikh-i-Jadíd
                     and his own Traveller's Narrative) that this work was written
                     by the Báb for Áqá Sayyid Yaḥyá of Dárab at Shíráz - a
                     supposition Browne considers reinforced by a passage on f. 9b
                     of this very manuscript addressing "O Yaḥyá" directly. The
                     colophon dates the transcription to Dhu'l-Ḥijja 14, AH 1296 (29
                     November 1879).</summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="BBF_8-item1">
                     <author key="">the Báb</author>
                     <title xml:lang="ar" key="">تفسیر سورة الکوثر</title>
                     <title xml:lang="en">Commentary on the Súratu'l-Kawthar</title>
                     <note>Colophon dated Dhu'l-Ḥijja 14, AH 1296 (29 November
                        1879); scribe not named.</note>
                     <note>Browne quotes several further passages from the
                        introduction as evidence of authorship and of the stage of
                        development of the Báb's ideas at the time of writing,
                        including a passage he suggests may allude to <persName
                           key="" role="att">Qurratu'l-'Ayn</persName>.</note>
                     <incipit xml:lang="ar" cert="low" resp="#ocr-draft">هذه
                        الصحیفة الجلیلة التی قد نزلت من سماء الابداع... بسم الله
                        الرحمن الرحیم الحمد لله الذی جعل طراز الواح کتاب الفلق...
                        (f. 2b)</incipit>
                     <explicit xml:lang="ar" cert="low" resp="#ocr-draft">... و
                        سبحان الله رب العرش عما یصفون و سلام علی المرسلین و الحمد
                        لله رب العالمین (ff. 115a-115b, followed by the
                        colophon)</explicit>
                     <textLang mainLang="ar">Arabic</textLang>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
